		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64357578" name="comment_link_64357578" href="//politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23274696&amp;cid=64357578" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64357578)" >No, politicians weigh contact by medium</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64357578" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64357578); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~drnb">drnb</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~drnb">( 2434720 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64357578"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64357578"><p><div class="quote"><p>Can Apps Turn Us Into Unpaid Lobbyists?</p> </div><p>No, politicians weigh contacts by medium. The more effort put into the contact the more heavily weighted. Generated contacts, emails, texts, are considered to have near zero value. Now a handwritten letter sent via postal mail, that's an important contact.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64357578">

